The value of \(n\) can be any positive integer up to 10. We then need to find the remainder when this count \(K\) is divided by 10. Key steps: 1. **Element-wise Analysis**: Each element in the universal set \(\{1, 2, \ldots, 10\}\) can be considered independently. For each element, the number of ways it can be included in the sequence is determined by the number of intervals in which it can be included (starting from position \(k\) and including all subsequent positions) or not included at all. 2. **Choices per Element**: For each element, there are \(n + 1\) choices (starting at each position from 1 to \(n\) or not included at all) when the sequence length is \(n\). Since there are 10 elements, the total number of sequences for a given \(n\) is \((n + 1)^{10}\). 3. **Summing Over All \(n\)**: The total number \(K\) is the sum of \((n + 1)^{10}\) for \(n\) from 1 to 10. We need to compute this sum modulo 10. Calculations: - For each \(n\) from 1 to 10, compute \((n + 1)^{10} \mod 10\): - \(n = 1\): \(2^{10} \mod 10 = 4\) - \(n = 2\): \(3^{10} \mod 10 = 9\) - \(n = 3\): \(4^{10} \mod 10 = 6\) - \(n = 4\): \(5^{10} \mod 10 = 5\) - \(n = 5\): \(6^{10} \mod 10 = 6\) - \(n = 6\): \(7^{10} \mod 10 = 9\) - \(n = 7\): \(8^{10} \mod 10 = 4\) - \(n = 8\): \(9^{10} \mod 10 = 1\) - \(n = 9\): \(10^{10} \mod 10 = 0\) - \(n = 10\): \(11^{10} \mod 10 = 1\) - Summing these results modulo 10: \[ 4 + 9 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 + 4 + 1 + 0 + 1 = 45 \] \[ 45 \mod 10 = 5 \] Thus, the remainder when \(K\) is divided by 10 is \(\boxed{5}\).
